In trapezoid $ABCD$ with bases $\overline{AB}$ and   $\overline{CD}$, we have $AB = 52$, $BC = 12$, $CD = 39$, and $DA = 5$. What is the area of $ABCD$?

[asy]
pair A,B,C,D;
A=(0,0);
B=(4,0);
C=(3.3,1);
D=(0.3,1);
label("$A$",A,S);
label("$B$",B,S);
label("$C$",C,N);
label("$D$",D,N);
label("52",(2,0),S);
label("39",(1.8,1),N);
label("5",(0.15,0.5),W);
label("12",(3.65,0.5),E);
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
[/asy]

solution:
First drop perpendiculars from $D$ and $C$ to $\overline{AB}$. Let $E$ and $F$ be the feet of the perpendiculars to $\overline{AB}$ from $D$ and $C$, respectively,  and let $$
h = DE = CF, \quad x = AE, \quad\text{and}\quad y = FB.
$$[asy]
pair A,B,C,D;
A=(0,0);
B=(4,0);
C=(3.3,1);
D=(0.3,1);
draw(D--(0.3,0));
draw(C--(3.3,0));
label("$E$",(0.3,0),SE);
label("$F$",(3.3,0),S);
label("$x$",(0.15,0),S);
label("$y$",(3.65,0),S);
label("$h$",(0.3,0.5),E);
label("$h$",(3.3,0.5),W);
label("$A$",A,SW);
label("$B$",B,S);
label("$C$",C,N);
label("$D$",D,N);
label("39",(2,0),S);
label("39",(1.8,1),N);
label("5",(0.15,0.5),W);
label("12",(3.65,0.5),E);
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
[/asy] Then $$
25 = h^2 + x^2, \quad 144 = h^2 + y^2, \quad\text{and}\quad 13 = x+y.
$$So $$
144 = h^2 + y^2 = h^2 + (13-x)^2 = h^2 + x^2 + 169 - 26x = 25 + 169- 26x,
$$which gives    $x = 50/26 = 25/13$, and $$
h= \sqrt{5^2 - \left(\frac{25}{13}\right)^2} = 5\sqrt{1 - \frac{25}{169}}
= 5\sqrt{\frac{144}{169}} = \frac{60}{13}.
$$Hence $$
\text{Area }(ABCD) = \frac{1}{2}(39 + 52)\cdot\frac{60}{13} = \boxed{210}.
$$$$
\text{OR}
$$Extend  $\overline{AD}$  and  $\overline{BC}$  to intersect at $P$. Since $\triangle PDC$ and $\triangle PAB$ are similar, we have $$
\frac{PD}{PD + 5} = \frac{39}{52} =
\frac{PC}{PC+12}.
$$So $PD = 15$ and $PC = 36$. Note that $15$, $36$, and $39$ are three times $5$, $12$, and $13$, respectively, so $\angle APB$ is a right angle. The area of the trapezoid is the difference of the areas of $\triangle PAB$ and $\triangle PDC$, so $$
\text{Area}(ABCD) =\frac{1}{2}(20)(48) - \frac{1}{2}(15)(36) = \boxed{210}.
$$[asy]
pair A,B,C,D;
A=(0,0);
B=(4,0);
C=(3.3,1);
D=(0.3,1);
label("$A$",A,S);
label("$B$",B,S);
label("$C$",C,E);
label("$D$",D,W);
draw((1.2,4)--C--D--cycle);
label("$P$",(1.2,4),N);
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
[/asy] $$
\text{OR}
$$Draw the line through $D$ parallel to  $\overline{BC}$, intersecting  $\overline{AB}$ at $E$. Then $BCDE$ is a parallelogram, so $DE = 12$, $EB = 39$, and $AE = 52 - 39 = 13.$ Thus $DE^2 + AD^2 = AE^2$, and  $\triangle ADE$ is a right triangle. Let $h$ be the altitude from $D$ to  $\overline{AE}$, and note that $$
\text{Area}(ADE) = \frac{1}{2}(5)(12) = \frac{1}{2}(13)(h),
$$so $h = 60/13$. Thus $$
\text{Area}(ABCD) =\frac{60}{13}\cdot\frac{1}{2}(39 + 52) = \boxed{210}.
$$[asy]
pair A,B,C,D;
A=(0,0);
B=(4,0);
C=(3.3,1);
D=(0.3,1);
label("$A$",A,S);
label("$B$",B,S);
label("$C$",C,N);
label("$D$",D,N);
draw(D--(1,0));
label("$E$",(1,0),S);
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
[/asy]

In the parallelogram, suppose that $d$ is opposite $a.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

A = (4,3);
B = (1,-2);
C = (8,-5);
D = B + C - A;

draw(A--B--D--C--cycle);
draw(A--D,dashed);
draw(B--C,dashed);

dot("$a$", A, N);
dot("$b$", B, W);
dot("$c$", C, E);
dot("$d$", D, S);
dot((A + D)/2);
[/asy]

Recall that in any parallelogram, the midpoints of the diagonals coincide.  Hence,
\[\frac{a + d}{2} = \frac{b + c}{2},\]which leads to $d = b + c - a.$

The complex number $d$ can also be opposite $b$ or $c,$ which leads to the possible values $d = a + c - b$ and $d = a + b - c.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

A = (4,3);
B = (1,-2);
C = (8,-5);

draw((B + C - A)--(A + C - B)--(A + B - C)--cycle,dashed);
draw(A--B--C--cycle,dashed);

dot("$a$", A, N);
dot("$b$", B, W);
dot("$c$", C, E);

dot("$b + c - a$", B + C - A, S);
dot("$a + c - b$", A + C - B, E);
dot("$a + b - c$", A + B - C, NW);
[/asy]

Thus, the possible values of $d$ are
\begin{align*}
b + c - a &= (1 - 2i) + (8 - 5i) - (4 + 3i) = \boxed{5 - 10i}, \\
a + c - b &= (4 + 3i) + (8 - 5i) - (1 - 2i) = \boxed{11}, \\
a + b - c &= (4 + 3i) + (1 - 2i) - (8 - 5i) = \boxed{-3 + 6i}.
\end{align*}

The focus of the parabola $y^2 = 4ax$ is $F = (a,0),$ and the directrix is $x = -a.$  Let $F',$ $P',$ $Q',$ and $R'$ be the projections of $F,$ $P,$ $Q,$ and $R$ onto the directrix, respectively.  Let $p = PP' = PF,$ $q = QQ' = QF,$ $a = P'F',$ and $B = Q'F'.$  Since $P,$ $F,$ and $Q$ are collinear,
\[\frac{p}{q} = \frac{a}{b}.\][asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

real y;
pair F, P, Q, R, S;
pair Fp, Pp, Qp, Rp;

F = (1,0);

path parab = ((-4)^2/4,-4);

for (y = -4; y <= 4; y = y + 0.01) {
  parab = parab--(y^2/4,y);
}

P = intersectionpoint(F--(F + 5*(1,2)),parab);
Q = intersectionpoint(F--(F - 5*(1,2)),parab);
R = reflect((0,0),(1,0))*(P);
S = extension(Q,R,(0,0),(1,0));
Fp = (-1,0);
Pp = (-1,P.y);
Qp = (-1,Q.y);
Rp = (-1,R.y);

draw(parab,red);
draw(P--Q);
draw(P--R);
draw(S--R);
draw((-2,0)--(4,0));
draw((0,-4)--(0,4));
draw((-1,-4)--(-1,4),dashed);
draw(P--Pp);
draw(Q--Qp);
draw(R--Rp);

label("$x = -a$", (-1,-4), dir(270));
label("$p$", (P + Pp)/2, N, red);
label("$p$", (P + F)/2, SE, red);
label("$q$", (Q + Qp)/2, dir(270), red);
label("$q$", (Q + F)/2, SE, red);
label("$a$", (Pp + Fp)/2, W, red);
label("$b$", (Qp + Fp)/2, W, red);
label("$p$", (Rp + R)/2, dir(270), red);

dot("$F$", F, SE);
dot("$P$", P, N);
dot("$Q$", Q, dir(270));
dot("$R$", R, dir(270));
dot("$F'$", S, NW);
dot("$P'$", Pp, W);
dot("$Q'$", Qp, W);
dot("$R'$", Rp, W);
[/asy]

Then
\[\frac{F'Q'}{F'R'} = \frac{b}{a} = \frac{q}{p} = \frac{QQ'}{RR'}.\]This means triangles $F'Q'Q$ and $F'R'R$ are similar, so line $QR$ intersects the $x$-axis at $F' = \boxed{(-a,0)}.$

