Then $\tan^2 \theta = \tan^2 \angle AOW.$  We see that $\tan^2 \angle AOW$ is maximized when $\angle AOW$ is maximized, which occurs when $\overline{OW}$ is tangent to the circle.  In this case, $\angle AWO = 90^\circ,$ so by Pythagoras, $OW = \sqrt{99},$ and $\tan \angle AOW = \frac{1}{\sqrt{99}},$ so
\[\tan^2 \angle AOW = \boxed{\frac{1}{99}}.\]

For $r = \cos 2 \theta \sec \theta,$
\[x = r \cos \theta = \cos 2 \theta\]and
\[y = r \sin \theta = \frac{\cos 2 \theta \sin \theta}{\cos \theta}.\][asy]
unitsize(1.5 cm);

real r, t, x, y;

t = -0.4*pi;
r = cos(2*t)/cos(t);
x = r*cos(t);
